<p style="text-align:justify;">the front when the doors open.  The Houses in the rears seem to have been built at random and are irregulaly placed to suit the conveniency of the owners<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  A mandane hut is spacious and has the fire place in the centre<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The roof is covered with willows and the base with Earth<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The door is of considerable size and situated in a porch.  The beds are raised from the ground and occupied according to <span class="DelHand-author">rank</span> <span class="AddHand-author">the</span> rank which the owners hold in the masters affection<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  His own bed is the first and the bed of his first wife next the others follow in succession<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The sofa upon which the master sits and receives his visits and upon which he sleeps when he is not disposed for the company of his wives is a handsome piece of workmanship made of small neat willows and covered <span class="DelHand-author">with</span> with painted Buffaloe skins.  Opposite the masters seat at the bottom of the hut Stands his collection of Medicines upon which he sets the highest value<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The most conspicuous in this collection are two Bulls heads painted &#8211; and beleived to afford protection to the Mandanes<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Then comes the place in which the horses are secured during the night<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[O]</span>nly one family</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">occupy</p>

